  <subsection>
    <title>Absolute Value and Inequality</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear_absolute_value_inequality">
      <title>Linear Absolute Value Inequality</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  A <term>linear absolute value inequality</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Inequality</h>
	    <h>Linear</h>
	    <h>Absolute Value</h>
	  </idx>
	  in the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is an expression that can be placed in one of the following forms
	  <ul>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \lt d</m>,
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \leq d</m>,
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \gt d</m>, or
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \geq d</m>.
	    </li>
	  </ul>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Let <m>d</m> be any positive real number.
      Recall from <xref ref="def-1_distance" /> that
      <me>\abs{d - 0} = \abs{0 - d} = \abs{d} = d</me>
      measures the distance between <m>d</m> and the origin on the number line.
      By looking at the number line, we can see the distance between <m>d</m> and the origin is the same as the distance from <m>-d</m> to the origin.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-abs_val_two_sol">
      <caption>The distance between <m>d</m> and the origin, and between <m>-d</m> and the origin.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-abs_val_two_sol">
	<latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_val_two_sol">
	  <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_val_two_sol.tex"/>
	</latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      We can confirm this algebraically using <xref ref="def-1_distance"/>:
      <me>\abs{-d - 0} = \abs{-d} = \sqrt{(-d)^2} = \sqrt{d^2} = \abs{d} = \abs{d - 0}</me>
      Hence for any positive number <m>d</m>, there are precisely two numbers that are <m>d</m> units away from the origin: <m>d</m> and <m>-d</m>.
      All other numbers are either more than <m>d</m> units away from the origin or less than <m>d</m> units away from the origin.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now consider an equation of the form <m>\abs{ax + by + c} = d</m>.
      The observation above tells us the solutions to this equation are the points <m>(x,y)</m> in the plane such that the number <m>ax + by + c</m> is <em>exactly</em> <m>d</m> units away from the origin.
      As the only two numbers that are <m>d</m> units away from the origin are <m>d</m> and <m>-d</m>, either 
      <me>ax + by + c = d \quad\text{or}\quad ax + by + c = -d</me>
      In standard form, we can recognize these as two parallel lines
      <me>ax + by = -c + d \quad\text{and}\quad ax + by = -c - d</me>
      Geometrically, this tells us the points between these lines make the number <m>ax + by + c</m> <em>less</em> than <m>d</m>, while the points outside these lines make the number <m>ax + by + c</m> <em>more</em> than <m>d</m>.
      This provides a pleasing geometric description of the solutions to the four types of linear absolute value inequalities:
      <ul>
	<li>
	  <p>
	    The solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \lt d</m> are the points that are between the lines <m>ax + by = -d - c </m> and <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>,
	  </p>
	</li>
	<li>
	  <p>
	    The solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \leq d</m> are the points that are either on or between the lines <m>ax + by = -d - c</m> and <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>,
	  </p>
	</li>
	<li>
	  <p>
	    The solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} > d</m> are the points that are outside the lines <m>ax + by = -c - d</m> and <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
	  </p>
	</li>
	<li>
	  <p>
	    The solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \geq d</m> are the points that are either on or outside the lines <m>ax + by = -c - d</m> and <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
	  </p>
	</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m> are the points between the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5</me>
	  Since <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> is the lower line and <m>2x + 3y = 5x</m> is the upper line, we can regard these as solutions to <alert>both</alert> of the linear inequalities
	  <me>-5 \lt 2x + 3y \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y \lt 5</me>
	  We can condense these as the compound inequality
	  <me>-5 \lt 2x + 3y \lt 5</me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>overlap</alert> between <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_lt_5"/> and <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_gt_-5"/>.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	    <latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_lt_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m> are the points that are either on or between the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5</me>
	  Since <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> is the lower line and <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> is the upper line, we can regard these as the points that are solutions to <alert>both</alert> of the linear inequalities
	  <me>-5 \leq 2x + 3y \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y \leq 5</me>
	  We can condense these into the compound inequality
	  <me>-5 \leq 2x + 3y \leq 5.</me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>overlap</alert> between <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_leq_5"/> and <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_geq_-5"/>.
	</p>
	<figure>
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.</caption>

	  <image>
	    <latex-image>
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_leq_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \gt 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m> are the points that are outside the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5</me>
	  Since <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> is the lower line and <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> is the upper line, we can regard these as solutions to <alert>either</alert> 
	  <me>
	    2x + 3y \lt -5
	    \quad\text{or}\quad
	    5 \lt 2x + 3y
	  </me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>combination</alert> of the graphs for the linear inequalities
	  <me>2x + 3 \lt -5
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  2x + 3y \gt 5.</me>
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \gt 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	    <latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_gt_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \geq 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \geq 5</m> are the points that are either on or outside the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5</me>
	  Since <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> is the lower line and <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> is the upper line, we can regard these as solutions to <alert>either</alert>
	  <me>2x + 3y \leq -5 \quad\text{or}\quad 5 \leq 2x + 3y</me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>combination</alert> of the graphs for the linear inequalities
	  <me>2x + 3 \leq -5
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  2x + 3y \geq 5.</me>
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_geq_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \geq 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_geq_5">
